\subsection{Documentation of expensive properties}
As evidenced by the \texttt{TwoElevators} run, the \texttt{TemporalInvariant} is significantly more "expensive" than safety invariants. While TLC explored all 50,653 states and verified safety in 10 seconds, it failed to complete the liveness check (cycle detection) within 12 minutes. This is because cycle detection requires searching for loops in the behavior graph, which has a higher computational complexity than the state-by-state validation used for safety.

\subsection{Operational Role of Actions}
The operational logic of the elevator system is governed by the following key actions:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{\texttt{PickNewDestination(p)}}: Represents a person's decision to travel. It updates a person's \texttt{destination} without immediately requesting the elevator.
    \item \textbf{\texttt{CallElevator(p)}}: The person requests service from their current floor, adding a request to \texttt{ActiveElevatorCalls}.
    \item \textbf{\texttt{DispatchElevator(c)}}: The system's controller assigns an elevator to a call based on proximity and current direction.
    \item \textbf{\texttt{MoveElevator(e)}}: Moves the elevator car between floors, provided the doors are closed and a direction is set.
    \item \textbf{\texttt{OpenElevatorDoors(e)}}: Occurs when an elevator arrives at a floor with a pending call or an internal button press.
    \item \textbf{\texttt{EnterElevator(e)}}: Facilitates the boarding process for people waiting for the elevator's current direction.
    \item \textbf{\texttt{ExitElevator(e)}}: People whose destination matches the current floor leave the car, resetting their \texttt{waiting} status to \texttt{FALSE}.
    \item \textbf{\texttt{CloseElevatorDoors(e)}}: Ensures the elevator cannot move until all eligible boarding/exiting actions are completed.
    \item \textbf{\texttt{StopElevator(e)}}: Resets an elevator to a \texttt{Stationary} state once all its assigned calls are fulfilled.
\end{itemize}

\section{Part 2: Fairness and Liveness Sensitivity Study}

\subsection{Controlled Fairness Experiment}
To analyze the impact of fairness assumptions on system progress, we conducted a sensitivity study by weakening the fairness requirements for the \texttt{DispatchElevator} action. Specifically, the \texttt{Strong Fairness} (SF) assumption on the dispatcher was replaced with \texttt{Weak Fairness} (WF) in the \texttt{TemporalAssumptions} definition:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Original:} $\forall c \in \texttt{ElevatorCall} : \texttt{SF\_Vars(DispatchElevator(c))}$
    \item \textbf{Modified:} $\forall c \in \texttt{ElevatorCall} : \texttt{WF\_Vars(DispatchElevator(c))}$
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Results and Liveness Violation}
Testing this modification on the baseline model (1 Elevator, 2 People, 3 Floors) resulted in a \textbf{Temporal Property Violation}. TLC identified a starvation scenario where the \texttt{TemporalInvariant} failed to hold.

