\end{table}

\subsection{Counterexample Analysis: Passenger Starvation}
The error trace provided by TLC revealed a "livelock" or starvation cycle. In this scenario, passenger $p_1$ at Floor 1 issues an "Up" call to Floor 2. However, $p_1$ is never serviced because the system enters an infinite loop where the elevator prioritizes passenger $p_2$.

\textbf{Mechanism of Failure:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item $p_1$ sets \texttt{waiting = TRUE}, enabling the \texttt{DispatchElevator} action for that floor.
    \item Passenger $p_2$ repeatedly requests rides between Floors 2 and 3.
    \item As the elevator moves to service $p_2$ or opens its doors, the conditions that make the elevator "available" to be dispatched for $p_1$ (e.g., being stationary or moving in the correct direction) are momentarily interrupted.
    \item Under \textbf{Weak Fairness}, the system is only required to execute an action if it remains \texttt{ENABLED} \textit{continuously}. Because the enablement of the dispatcher for $p_1$ "flickers" as the elevator services $p_2$, the system is mathematically permitted to ignore $p_1$ indefinitely.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Conclusion on Fairness Sensitivity}
This experiment demonstrates that \textbf{Strong Fairness} is a strict requirement for the \texttt{DispatchElevator} action. Unlike \texttt{Weak Fairness}, \texttt{Strong Fairness} guarantees that if an action is enabled \textit{infinitely often} (even if interrupted), it must eventually occur. In a multi-passenger environment where concurrent requests compete for resources, SF ensures that every call is eventually dispatched, regardless of how "busy" the elevator is with other passengers.

\section{Part 3: Custom Properties and Verification}

In accordance with the project requirements for a three-member group, we implemented and verified three additional properties. These properties cover individual elevator safety, multi-elevator coordination, and passenger progress.

\subsection{Property 1: Physical Motion Safety}
\textbf{Definition:} This invariant ensures an elevator car does not transition floors while doors are open.
$\mathrm{DoorsClosedWhileMoving} := \forall e \in \mathrm{Elevator}:\ \mathrm{ElevatorState}[e].\mathrm{direction} \neq \text{"Stationary"} \Rightarrow \neg\mathrm{ElevatorState}[e].\mathrm{doorsOpen}$

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Status:} \textbf{Failed}.
    \item \textbf{Analysis:} TLC identified a violation during the \texttt{DispatchElevator} action. In this specification, the \texttt{direction} variable represents the \textit{intent} or assignment of the car. Since the car is assigned a direction before the doors finish closing at its current floor, the property is violated.
    \item \textbf{Insight:} This failure highlights the distinction between high-level logic (intent) and physical system states (motion) within a TLA+ specification.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Property 2: Multi-Elevator Coordination}
\textbf{Definition:} This invariant ensures that two different elevators never open their doors on the same floor simultaneously, preventing redundant service and passenger confusion.
$\mathrm{NoDualDoorOpen} := \forall e_1, e_2 \in \mathrm{Elevator}:\ (e_1 \neq e_2 \land \mathrm{ElevatorState}[e_1].\mathrm{doorsOpen} \land \mathrm{ElevatorState}[e_2].\mathrm{doorsOpen}) \Rightarrow \mathrm{ElevatorState}[e_1].\mathrm{floor} \neq \mathrm{ElevatorState}[e_2].\mathrm{floor}$

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Status:} \textbf{Passed}.
    \item \textbf{Configuration:} Verified on \texttt{model\_TwoElevators} (50,653 states).
    \item \textbf{Analysis:} The success of this property confirms that the dispatcher logic effectively partitions the floor space, ensuring that once a call is assigned, other cars do not interfere with that specific floor request.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Property 3: Guaranteed Boarding (Liveness)}
\textbf{Definition:} This temporal property ensures that a passenger in a \texttt{waiting} state will eventually enter an elevator car, verifying the absence of "platform starvation."
$\mathrm{EventuallyPickedUp} := \forall p \in \mathrm{Person}:\ \mathrm{PersonState}[p].\mathrm{waiting}\;\sim\!>\;(\mathrm{PersonState}[p].\mathrm{location} \in \mathrm{Elevator})$

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Status:} \textbf{Passed}.
    \item \textbf{Configuration:} Verified on \texttt{model\_baseline} (2,685 states).
    \item \textbf{Analysis:} Unlike the safety invariants, this property is a "Progress" guarantee. It relies entirely on the \textbf{Strong Fairness} assumptions established in Part 2. Its success confirms that our fairness constraints are sufficient to ensure that the dispatcher cannot ignore a call indefinitely, even if other concurrent requests are available.
\end{itemize}

